\title{Hunting For Persistence Mechanisms In Windows}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{threat-hunting}

\tag{mitre-attack}

\tag{persistence}

\tag{windows}

\tag{registry}

\tag{siem}

\tag{proactive-detection}

\meta{version}{"1.0"}

\meta{description}{Systematically hunt for adversary persistence mechanisms across Windows endpoints including registry, services, startup folders, and WMI subscriptions.}

\subtree{
\title{Hunting for Persistence Mechanisms in Windows}
\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{During periodic proactive threat hunts for dormant backdoors}
\li{After an incident to identify all persistence mechanisms an attacker planted}
\li{When investigating unusual services, scheduled tasks, or startup entries}
\li{When threat intel reports describe new persistence techniques in the wild}
\li{During security posture assessments to identify unauthorized persistent software}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Sysmon deployed with Event IDs 12/13/14 (Registry), 19/20/21 (WMI), 1 (Process Creation)}
\li{Windows Security Event forwarding for 4697 (Service Install), 4698 (Scheduled Task)}
\li{EDR with registry and file monitoring capabilities}
\li{PowerShell script block logging enabled (Event ID 4104)}
\li{Autoruns or equivalent baseline of legitimate persistent entries}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Enumerate Known Persistence Locations}: Build a comprehensive list of Windows persistence points (Run keys, services, scheduled tasks, WMI, startup folder, DLL search order, COM hijacks, AppInit DLLs, Image File Execution Options).}
\li{\strong{Collect Endpoint Data}: Use EDR, Sysmon, or Velociraptor to collect current persistence artifacts from endpoints across the environment.}
\li{\strong{Baseline Legitimate Persistence}: Compare collected data against known-good baselines (Autoruns snapshots, GPO-deployed entries, SCCM configurations).}
\li{\strong{Identify Anomalies}: Flag new, unsigned, or unknown entries in persistence locations that deviate from the baseline.}
\li{\strong{Investigate Suspicious Entries}: For each anomaly, examine the binary it points to, its digital signature, file hash, and creation timestamp.}
\li{\strong{Correlate with Process Activity}: Link persistence entries to process execution, network activity, and user login events.}
\li{\strong{Document and Remediate}: Record findings, remove malicious persistence, and update detection rules.}
}
}

